var tafsirData_15 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Ra": "These are letters from the Arabic alphabet that appear at the beginning of certain surahs. Their precise meaning is known only to Allah. They serve to capture attention and demonstrate that the Quran, though composed of familiar letters, is a miraculous revelation that no human could produce. The Arabs, despite being masters of the Arabic language, could not replicate even a single chapter of it.",
    "These are the verses of the Book": "This refers to the Quran itself—the divine scripture sent down from Allah. The word 'verses' (ayat) also means 'signs,' indicating that each verse is a miraculous sign from the Creator, containing guidance, wisdom, and evidence of its divine origin.",
    "the clear Quran": "The Quran is described as 'clear' (mubeen), meaning it is plain, manifest, and easy to understand for those who sincerely seek the truth. It makes the path of guidance crystal clear, distinguishing right from wrong, truth from falsehood. There is no ambiguity in its core message of monotheism, morality, and accountability."
  },
  2: {
    "˹The day will come when˺ the disbelievers will certainly wish": "A time is coming—specifically the Day of Judgment or even at the moment of death—when those who rejected faith will be overwhelmed with regret. They will desperately wish they had made different choices in life. This is a powerful warning that the consequences of disbelief are so severe that even the most stubborn rejecters will wish they could turn back time.",
    "they had submitted ˹to Allah˺": "They will wish they had been Muslims—those who submitted their will to Allah, followed His guidance, and obeyed His commands. The word 'Muslim' means one who submits to Allah. On that Day, when they witness the punishment awaiting them and the reward given to the believers, their regret will be unbearable. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said that on the Day of Judgment, some disbelievers will wish they could become dust rather than face their fate."
  },
  3: {
    "˹So˺ let them eat and enjoy themselves": "This is a statement of warning, not permission. Allah is telling the Prophet (peace be upon him) to leave these disbelievers to their worldly pursuits. Let them indulge in food, pleasures, and material comforts. They are like cattle that eat and enjoy without thinking about their purpose or destination. Their enjoyment is temporary and will soon come to an end.",
    "and be diverted by ˹false˺ hope": "False hope is one of Satan's most effective tools. These people keep postponing repentance, thinking they have plenty of time, or hoping that perhaps there is no afterlife at all. They are distracted by dreams of wealth, long life, and worldly success. This false hope keeps them heedless of the reality of death and accountability. Many people live their entire lives chasing illusions, never preparing for the inevitable meeting with their Lord.",
    "for they will soon know": "This is a stern warning. Their knowledge will come, but it will be too late. They will soon discover the truth—either at the moment of death when the veil is lifted, or on the Day of Judgment when they stand before Allah. At that point, their false hopes will shatter, and the reality they denied will become painfully clear."
  },
  4: {
    "We have never destroyed a society": "Allah is establishing a divine principle here. Throughout history, many nations and civilizations have been destroyed due to their rebellion against Allah and rejection of His messengers. Think of the people of Noah, the people of Lot, the people of Pharaoh, and many others. However, none of these destructions happened randomly or hastily.",
    "without a destined term": "Every nation has a fixed, predetermined time appointed by Allah. This appointed term (kitab ma'loom) is recorded in Allah's knowledge and cannot be changed. Allah, in His wisdom and justice, gives every people sufficient time to receive the message, reflect upon it, and make their choice. He sends them messengers and warnings. Only when they persistently reject the truth and their appointed time expires does the punishment come. This shows Allah's perfect justice—He never punishes a people without first giving them full opportunity to repent."
  },
  5: {
    "No people can advance their doom": "When Allah has decreed a specific time for a nation's end, they cannot bring it upon themselves earlier, no matter what they do. Even if they rush headlong into sin and corruption, their destruction will not come before its appointed time. This also serves as a reminder that the delay in punishment should not be mistaken for approval or weakness on Allah's part.",
    "nor can they delay it": "Similarly, when the appointed time arrives, no power in existence can postpone it—not wealth, not armies, not technology, not alliances. When Allah's decree comes, it is final and unstoppable. This applies to nations collectively and to individuals as well. The lesson here is profound: use the time you have wisely, for you never know when your appointed term will arrive, and when it does, there will be no extensions."
  },
  6: {
    "They say, \"O you to whom the Reminder is revealed!": "The pagans of Makkah addressed the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) in a mocking and sarcastic tone. By saying 'the one to whom the Reminder is revealed,' they were not acknowledging the truth of his prophethood. Rather, they were sarcastically referring to his claim of receiving divine revelation. The 'Reminder' (Dhikr) refers to the Quran, which is called so because it reminds humanity of their purpose, their Lord, and the Day of Judgment.",
    "You must be insane!": "This was their desperate accusation against the Prophet (peace be upon him). Unable to refute his message logically, they resorted to personal attacks and character assassination. They called him a madman (majnoon)—someone possessed by jinn or mentally unstable. This accusation was obviously false, as the Prophet was known among them as Al-Ameen (the Trustworthy) and Al-Sadiq (the Truthful) even before his prophethood. His character, wisdom, and eloquence were evident to all. This pattern of accusing prophets of madness was common throughout history—the people of Noah, for instance, made similar accusations against him."
  },
  7: {
    "Why do you not bring us the angels": "The disbelievers demanded visible miracles according to their own whims. They wanted to see angels descend from the sky as proof of the Prophet's truthfulness. This demand stemmed from arrogance, not genuine seeking of truth. They had already received the greatest miracle—the Quran itself—but they dismissed it. People who are determined to disbelieve will always find excuses and demand more signs, even if every miracle were shown to them.",
    "if what you say is true?": "They challenged the Prophet's claim to prophethood by setting their own conditions for belief. However, faith is not meant to work this way. Allah sends guidance and evidence according to His wisdom, not according to human demands. The Quran itself, with its linguistic perfection, accurate prophecies, and transformative power, was more than sufficient proof for anyone sincerely seeking truth."
  },
  8: {
    "We do not send the angels down except for a just cause": "Allah responds to their arrogant demand. Angels are not sent down for entertainment or to satisfy human curiosity. When angels descend visibly to a disbelieving people, it is typically for one of two purposes: to deliver revelation to prophets, or to execute Allah's punishment. Angels came to the people of Lot to destroy them. They do not come as circus performers to prove a point to mockers.",
    "and then ˹the end of˺ the disbelievers will not be delayed": "This is a severe warning. If Allah were to send angels as they demanded, it would be for their destruction, and at that point, they would receive no more time for repentance. The delay they currently enjoy—which they mistake for permission to continue in disbelief—would end immediately. So in reality, it is Allah's mercy that He has not sent the angels to them in the manner they request."
  },
  9: {
    "It is certainly We Who have revealed the Reminder": "Allah emphatically declares His ownership of the Quran's revelation. The pronoun 'We' here is the royal 'We' indicating majesty and power. The Quran (the Reminder) came from Allah alone—it is not the words of Muhammad (peace be upon him), nor the product of any human or jinn. This divine origin guarantees its truthfulness and authority.",
    "and it is certainly We Who will preserve it": "This is one of the most powerful promises in the Quran. Allah Himself has taken the responsibility of preserving the Quran from any corruption, alteration, addition, or deletion. Unlike previous scriptures which were entrusted to humans and subsequently altered over time, the Quran remains exactly as it was revealed over 1400 years ago. This preservation is miraculous and historically verifiable—millions have memorized it completely, manuscripts from the earliest periods match today's text, and the oral transmission chain remains unbroken. This promise distinguishes the Quran from all other religious texts and is a clear sign of its divine origin."
  },
  10: {
    "Indeed, We sent messengers before you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah consoles the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) by reminding him that he is not alone in facing rejection. Many messengers came before him—Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and countless others—all sent with the same core message of worshipping Allah alone.",
    "among the groups of early peoples": "These messengers were sent to various nations, communities, and civilizations throughout human history. The word 'shiya' (groups/sects) indicates that every significant human community received divine guidance. Allah's mercy ensured that no people were left without a warner to guide them to the truth."
  },
  11: {
    "but no messenger ever came to them": "This establishes a universal historical pattern. Every single messenger, without exception, faced opposition from his people. This was not due to any fault in the messengers or their message.",
    "without being mocked": "Mockery, ridicule, and rejection were the standard responses of disbelieving peoples toward their prophets. Noah was mocked for building the ark. Abraham was ridiculed for rejecting idols. Moses was opposed by Pharaoh. Jesus was rejected by many of his own people. This pattern repeats because the message of truth challenges people's desires, traditions, and power structures. Those who benefit from the status quo resist change. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) should therefore not be disheartened—he is in noble company, and his experience is part of the prophetic legacy."
  },
  12: {
    "This is how We allow disbelief ˹to steep˺ into the hearts of the wicked": "When people persistently choose mockery and rejection over sincere reflection, Allah allows disbelief to penetrate and settle deep in their hearts. This is not injustice from Allah; rather, it is a consequence of their own choices. Just as a person who repeatedly lies becomes a habitual liar, one who repeatedly rejects truth has their heart sealed against it. The word 'mujrimeen' (criminals/wicked) indicates those who have committed themselves to sin and rejection. Their hearts become like hardened soil that cannot absorb rain—the guidance falls upon them but does not penetrate. This is a warning to never take the truth lightly, for persistent rejection leads to spiritual blindness."
  },
  13: {
    "They would not believe in this ˹Quran˺": "Despite its clear guidance, miraculous nature, and transformative message, these stubborn disbelievers refuse to accept the Quran. Their refusal is not due to lack of evidence but due to arrogance, following desires, and attachment to the ways of their ancestors.",
    "despite the ˹many˺ examples of those ˹destroyed˺ before": "History is filled with examples of nations destroyed for rejecting their messengers—the floods that drowned Noah's people, the destruction of the people of 'Ad and Thamud, the cities of Lot overturned, Pharaoh's army drowned. These historical precedents should serve as powerful warnings. The ruins of some of these civilizations were even visible to the Arabs of that time along their trade routes. Yet despite all these examples, the disbelievers of Makkah failed to take heed. Those who ignore history are doomed to repeat its mistakes."
  },
  14: {
    "And even if We opened for them a gate to heaven": "Allah presents a hypothetical scenario to illustrate the extreme stubbornness of these disbelievers. Imagine if Allah were to open an actual gateway into the heavens for them—a clear, undeniable, supernatural miracle.",
    "through which they continued to ascend": "And imagine they were allowed to physically ascend through this gate, climbing up into the heavens, witnessing the unseen realm with their own eyes. This would be an experience beyond any doubt—direct, personal, sensory proof of the reality they deny."
  },
  15: {
    "still they would say, \"Our eyes have truly been dazzled!": "Even after such an extraordinary experience, these hardened disbelievers would find excuses. They would claim their eyes were playing tricks on them, that they were experiencing some kind of optical illusion or hallucination. The word 'sukkirat' suggests their vision was blocked or intoxicated—they would blame their own senses rather than accept the truth.",
    "In fact, we must have been bewitched.\"": "Going even further, they would attribute this miraculous experience to magic or sorcery rather than acknowledge it as a sign from Allah. This verse powerfully demonstrates that for some people, no amount of evidence will ever suffice. Their problem is not intellectual—it is spiritual. Their hearts are sealed, and they are determined to disbelieve regardless of what they witness. This is why Allah does not send miracles merely on demand; those who reject guidance will reject any miracle while those who sincerely seek truth will find the Quran itself to be the greatest miracle."
  },
  16: {
    "Indeed, We have placed constellations in the sky": "Allah draws attention to the magnificent celestial order. The word 'burooj' refers to the great constellations, the celestial mansions, or the positions of stars that form recognizable patterns. These constellations have been used throughout human history for navigation, marking seasons, and understanding time. Their precise positioning and movement reflect the perfect planning of the Creator.",
    "and adorned it for all to see": "The night sky is not just functional—it is beautiful. Allah designed it to be a source of wonder and contemplation for anyone who looks up. The stars, planets, and galaxies are decorations that inspire awe and reflection. This beauty is intentional, pointing to a Creator who values aesthetics and wants His creation to appreciate His artistry. Every person who gazes at a star-filled sky and feels wonder is experiencing a sign of Allah."
  },
  17: {
    "And We protected it from every accursed devil": "The heavens are guarded and protected by Allah's command. The devils (shayateen) who are cursed and expelled from Allah's mercy are prevented from accessing the higher realms where divine decrees are communicated. The word 'rajeem' means pelted, stoned, or accursed—these devils are driven away and have no authority in the heavens. This protection ensures the purity of divine revelation and communication."
  },
  18: {
    "except the one eavesdropping": "Some devils attempt to steal fragments of information from the heavenly realm by secretly listening to the angels' conversations. They try to snatch pieces of knowledge about future events or divine decrees. This eavesdropping is unauthorized and immediately punished.",
    "who is then pursued by a visible flare": "When a devil attempts to steal heavenly secrets, a bright flaming meteor (shihab mubeen) is sent to chase and strike it. This phenomenon is mentioned in several places in the Quran. The shooting stars we see are described as missiles against these eavesdropping devils. Before the coming of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), the devils had more access to such information, but afterward, the guarding intensified significantly. This is why fortune-tellers who relied on jinn for information became less accurate after the Prophet's mission began."
  },
  19: {
    "As for the earth, We spread it out": "Allah extended and stretched out the earth, making it suitable for habitation. From the human perspective, the earth appears spread out and expansive, providing space for life, agriculture, travel, and settlement. This spreading out is one of Allah's favors that makes life possible.",
    "and placed upon it firm mountains": "The mountains (rawasi) are like pegs or anchors that stabilize the earth. They prevent excessive shaking and provide balance to the earth's crust. Mountains also serve as water towers, storing snow and ice that melts to feed rivers and provide fresh water. They affect weather patterns and create diverse ecosystems.",
    "and caused everything to grow there in perfect balance": "Every plant, crop, fruit, and vegetation grows according to a precise measure (mawzoon). Nothing in nature is random or excessive. Each species has its designated quantity, location, and growing conditions. The balance of oxygen and carbon dioxide, the water cycle, the food chain—everything operates in perfect harmony. This ecological balance is a sign of deliberate, intelligent design."
  },
  20: {
    "And We made in it means of sustenance for you": "Allah has placed in the earth everything humans need to live—food, water, shelter materials, clothing fibers, medicines, and countless other provisions. These means of livelihood (ma'ayish) include agriculture, mining, animal husbandry, and all forms of sustenance that humans derive from the earth.",
    "and others, who you do not provide for": "This is a humbling reminder. Humans share the earth with countless other creatures—animals, birds, insects, sea life—all of whom are sustained by Allah, not by humans. You may think you provide for your livestock or pets, but in reality, it is Allah who creates the grass they eat, the water they drink, and the very food you give them. Every creature, from the largest whale to the smallest ant, receives its sustenance from Allah's provision. Recognizing this should increase both gratitude and humility."
  },
  21: {
    "There is not any means ˹of sustenance˺ whose reserves We do not hold": "Every resource in existence—water, minerals, food, energy, even abstract blessings like health and knowledge—has its ultimate source and treasury with Allah. Nothing comes into being or is sustained except from His infinite reserves. Humans may discover, extract, or process these resources, but they cannot create them from nothing.",
    "only bringing it forth in precise measure": "Allah releases these provisions according to exact, predetermined amounts based on His infinite wisdom. Rain falls in measured quantities—enough to sustain life but not flood everything constantly. Crops grow in appropriate seasons. Resources are distributed across the earth. If Allah were to release all provisions at once or without measure, the system would collapse. This precise measuring demonstrates that nothing is random in creation; everything operates according to divine calculation and wisdom."
  },
  22: {
    "We send fertilizing winds": "The winds serve multiple purposes in Allah's design. They carry pollen from male to female plants, enabling fertilization and reproduction of crops and forests. They also carry water vapor from the oceans, forming clouds that travel to distant lands. The word 'lawaqih' (fertilizing) captures both these roles—winds that bring life and productivity to the earth.",
    "and bring down rain from the sky for you to drink": "The water cycle is one of Allah's greatest blessings. Water evaporates from oceans, is carried by winds, forms clouds, and falls as fresh, drinkable rain. This purified water sustains all life on earth. Without this system, life would be impossible. Every drop of water you drink has been through this divine purification system.",
    "It is not you who hold its reserves": "Humans cannot store or control the water cycle. You cannot decide when or where it rains. You cannot create water from nothing. Your reservoirs and water tanks are merely temporary holding places for what Allah has already sent down. If Allah were to withhold rain, all the technology in the world could not produce it. This should inspire deep gratitude and acknowledgment of complete dependence on Allah."
  },
  23: {
    "Surely it is We Who give life": "Allah alone has the power to bring things into existence and give them life. From the formation of a baby in the womb to the sprouting of a seed in the soil, all life originates from Allah's command. No scientist can create life from nothing—they can only work with what Allah has already created.",
    "and cause death": "Just as Allah gives life, He takes it away. Every soul will taste death at its appointed time, and no one can prevent or delay it. Death is not an end but a transition, and it is entirely under Allah's control.",
    "And We are the ˹Eternal˺ Successor": "After all creatures perish, Allah alone remains. He inherits everything in the heavens and the earth. All property, kingdoms, and possessions will return to Him. He was before all creation, and He will remain after all creation ceases. This title reminds us that our ownership of anything is temporary—ultimately, everything belongs to and returns to Allah."
  },
  24: {
    "We certainly know those who have gone before you": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all of humanity from the beginning of creation. Every person who lived and died before you—from Adam to the most recent deceased—is known to Allah in complete detail. Their deeds, their thoughts, their destinations are all recorded and known.",
    "and those who will come after ˹you˺": "Similarly, Allah knows everyone who will be born until the Day of Judgment. Every future generation, every unborn child, every person who will ever exist—Allah knows them already. His knowledge is not limited by time. Past, present, and future are all equal before His infinite awareness. This comprehensive knowledge means that nothing escapes His account, and everyone will be held responsible for their deeds."
  },
  25: {
    "Surely your Lord ˹alone˺ will gather them together ˹for judgment˺": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will resurrect and gather every human being who ever lived—from the first to the last. No one will escape this gathering. Whether they were buried, cremated, drowned, or eaten by animals, Allah will reassemble them completely. This gathering is for the purpose of final judgment and recompense.",
    "He is truly All-Wise": "Allah's wisdom (Hakeem) ensures that the judgment will be perfectly fair. He knows exactly what each person deserves based on their circumstances, intentions, and actions. His wisdom means nothing is arbitrary—every decision has perfect reasoning behind it.",
    "All-Knowing": "His knowledge ('Aleem) guarantees that nothing will be overlooked or forgotten. Every deed, every word, every secret thought is recorded. No injustice will occur because Allah knows the complete truth about everyone and everything. The combination of perfect wisdom and complete knowledge means that the Day of Judgment will be absolutely just."
  },
  26: {
    "Indeed, We created man": "Allah announces the creation of the human being, specifically referring to Adam (peace be upon him), the father of all humanity. This is a declaration of human origins, establishing that humans are created beings with a Creator.",
    "from sounding clay moulded from black mud": "The original human, Adam, was created from clay that had specific characteristics. The word 'salsal' refers to dry clay that makes a sound when struck—like pottery. This clay was derived from 'hama' masnoon'—aged, black mud that had altered over time. Allah took this humble material and fashioned it into the most honored of creation. This origin should humble every human being—no matter how proud or powerful, we all come from mud. Yet it should also honor us, as Allah chose to create us with His own hands and breathe His spirit into us."
  },
  27: {
    "As for the jinn, We created them earlier": "Before the creation of Adam and humanity, Allah created another species of intelligent beings—the jinn. They existed on earth before humans and will be held accountable for their deeds just like humans. Among them was Iblis (Satan), who later refused to prostrate to Adam.",
    "from smokeless fire": "While humans were created from clay/earth, jinn were created from a different element—fire. Specifically, 'nar as-samoom' refers to intensely hot, smokeless fire, like the hottest part of a flame. This different origin explains some of the jinn's different properties—they are normally invisible to humans, can travel great distances quickly, and have different physical constraints. Understanding that jinn are created beings helps us recognize that they too are subject to Allah's power and have no divinity themselves."
  },
  28: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet˺ when your Lord said to the angels": "Allah reminds the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him)—and through him, all of humanity—of a pivotal moment in cosmic history. Before creating Adam, Allah informed the angels of His plan. This announcement demonstrates that Allah acts with purpose and informs His creation of significant events.",
    "\"I am going to create a human being": "Allah declared His intention to create a new being—a human (bashar). This human would be different from the angels and the jinn, created for a special purpose on earth.",
    "from sounding clay moulded from black mud": "Allah specified the material from which this new creation would be formed—humble clay derived from aged mud. This emphasis on the material origin appears multiple times, perhaps to preempt any arrogance humans might later develop. Despite our noble purpose and honored status, our physical origin is earthly and humble."
  },
  29: {
    "So when I have fashioned him": "Allah describes the careful formation of Adam. The word 'sawwaytuhu' implies perfecting, proportioning, and completing the physical form. Allah shaped Adam with His own hands (as mentioned in other verses), giving him the best form and perfect proportions. This fashioning was deliberate and careful, not random or haphazard.",
    "and had a spirit of My Own ˹creation˺ breathed into him": "After the physical form was complete, Allah breathed into Adam a spirit (rooh). The phrase 'from My spirit' indicates honor and special creation—it does not mean a part of Allah entered Adam, but that the spirit was a special, noble creation directly from Allah. This spirit is what gives humans life, consciousness, and the capacity to know Allah. It elevates humans above mere physical existence.",
    "fall down in prostration to him": "Allah commanded the angels to prostrate before Adam. This prostration was not worship (which belongs only to Allah) but a prostration of honor and respect, acknowledging Adam's special status as Allah's vicegerent on earth. All the angels obeyed this command, but Iblis, who was present among them, refused out of arrogance. This refusal led to his expulsion from Allah's mercy and his eternal enmity toward humanity. The story continues in subsequent verses, showing how pride and arrogance can lead to the worst of downfalls."
  },
  30: {
    "So the angels prostrated all together": "When Allah commanded the angels to prostrate before Adam, every single angel obeyed without hesitation or delay. The double emphasis in the Arabic ('kulluhum ajma'oon' - all of them, together) stresses that not a single angel disobeyed. This demonstrates the perfect obedience of the angels—they do not question Allah's commands or act upon their own desires. They recognized that prostrating to Adam was not worship of Adam, but obedience to Allah who commanded them. This immediate, complete submission is the hallmark of angelic nature and serves as a model for how believers should respond to divine commands."
  },
  31: {
    "but not Iblîs": "Iblis is the personal name of Satan (Shaytan). He was not an angel but a jinn who had risen to be among the angels due to his extensive worship of Allah. Being a jinn, he possessed free will, unlike the angels who are created to obey. This free will made his test meaningful—and his failure catastrophic.",
    "who refused to prostrate with the others": "Iblis made a deliberate, conscious choice to disobey Allah's direct command. The word 'aba' (refused) indicates stubborn, willful rejection—not a mistake or moment of weakness. He saw all the angels prostrating and chose to remain standing in arrogance. This single act of defiance, rooted in pride, transformed him from a devoted worshipper into the accursed enemy of humanity. His story serves as the ultimate warning against arrogance and disobedience."
  },
  32: {
    "Allah asked, \"O Iblîs! What is the matter with you": "Allah addressed Iblis directly, giving him an opportunity to explain himself. This was not because Allah needed to know—He knows all things—but to establish Iblis's guilt through his own words and to teach us the nature of his crime. Allah's question also demonstrates His justice; even the one who would become His greatest enemy was given a chance to speak.",
    "that you did not join others in prostration?\"": "Allah pointed out that Iblis stood alone in his disobedience while every other being present had complied. This highlights the isolation that comes with arrogance and sin. When you choose to disobey Allah, you separate yourself from the community of the obedient, standing alone in your rebellion."
  },
  33: {
    "He replied, \"It is not for me to prostrate to a human": "Iblis revealed his arrogance in his response. He believed he was too superior to bow before a human being. Notice he did not apologize or seek forgiveness—he justified his disobedience. He essentially told Allah that His command was unreasonable. This is the essence of arrogance: placing your own judgment above Allah's command.",
    "You created from sounding clay moulded from black mud.\"": "Iblis looked down upon Adam's origin, considering clay and mud to be lowly materials. In another verse (7:12), he explicitly states his reasoning: 'I am better than him. You created me from fire and created him from clay.' He assumed that his fiery origin made him superior. This flawed logic ignored the fact that worth is not determined by material composition but by Allah's decree. Iblis focused on the physical and ignored the spiritual—he failed to recognize that Allah had honored Adam by fashioning him with His own hands and breathing into him from His spirit. This teaches us never to judge others based on external factors like race, wealth, or origin."
  },
  34: {
    "Allah commanded, \"Then get out of Paradise": "The consequence of Iblis's arrogance was immediate expulsion. He was cast out from the honored position he had held among the angels and from Paradise itself. All his previous worship and devotion became worthless because of this single act of proud disobedience. This teaches us that arrogance can nullify a lifetime of good deeds. No amount of worship matters if the heart is filled with pride.",
    "for you are truly cursed": "The word 'rajeem' means pelted, driven away, or accursed. Iblis was not just removed—he was expelled in disgrace, forever cut off from Allah's mercy. The same word is used for the devils who try to eavesdrop on heavenly communications and are pelted with flaming meteors. From this moment, Iblis became the embodiment of evil, the sworn enemy of Allah and humanity."
  },
  35: {
    "And surely upon you is condemnation until the Day of Judgment": "Allah's curse (la'nah) upon Iblis is permanent and extends until the Day of Judgment. This curse means complete removal from Allah's mercy and blessings. While humans who sin can repent and seek forgiveness, Iblis's curse is sealed because he refuses to repent. His arrogance prevents him from ever acknowledging his wrong. The curse continues until the Day of Judgment, after which his punishment in Hell will be eternal. This finality shows the severity of arrogance in Allah's sight—it is the sin that led to the first disobedience and remains the root of most evil."
  },
  36: {
    "Satan appealed, \"My Lord!": "Despite his arrogance and disobedience, Iblis still acknowledged Allah as his Lord (Rabb). He knew Allah was his Creator and Sustainer. His problem was not a lack of knowledge about Allah—it was pride and refusal to submit. This teaches us that merely knowing Allah exists is not enough; true faith requires humble submission.",
    "Then delay my end until the Day of their resurrection.\"": "Iblis requested to be kept alive until the Day when humans will be resurrected. His purpose was clear—he wanted time to mislead and corrupt the children of Adam, the very creation he resented. Rather than accepting his punishment and repenting, he sought the means to drag others down with him. This request shows his malicious nature; his focus shifted entirely to revenge against humanity."
  },
  37: {
    "Allah said, \"You will be delayed": "Allah granted Iblis's request for respite. This was not because Iblis deserved it, but because it served Allah's greater wisdom. By allowing Satan to exist and tempt humanity, Allah created a meaningful test for human beings. Our struggle against Satan's whispers is part of our spiritual development. Those who resist temptation and remain faithful demonstrate their true worth. Without the test, there would be no distinction between the sincere believers and the hypocrites."
  },
  38: {
    "until the appointed Day.\"": "Allah specified that Iblis would be given respite until a known, appointed time. This is understood by scholars to be the time of the first blowing of the Trumpet, when all creation will die, rather than the Day of Resurrection itself. So Iblis will not live to see the Resurrection—he will die like all other creatures before it. Allah's response shows that even Satan is completely under Allah's control. He exists only because Allah permits it, and he will die when Allah decrees. He has no independent power."
  },
  39: {
    "Satan responded, \"My Lord! For allowing me to stray": "Iblis blamed Allah for his own misguidance, saying 'because You caused me to stray.' This is the way of Satan and those who follow him—never accepting responsibility for their own choices, always blaming others, even blaming Allah. In reality, Allah did not force Iblis to disobey; Iblis chose pride over obedience. Allah only allowed the consequences of Iblis's own choice to unfold. This blame-shifting is a common tactic that Satan uses on humans as well—making them feel they had no choice or that circumstances forced them to sin.",
    "I will surely tempt them on earth": "Iblis announced his plan: he would make the earth a place of temptation, beautifying sins and evil deeds in the eyes of humans. The word 'uzayyin' means to adorn, decorate, and make attractive. This is Satan's primary strategy—he makes forbidden things look appealing, and he makes obedience to Allah seem boring or difficult. He decorates falsehood to look like truth, makes temporary pleasures seem worth eternal loss.",
    "and mislead them all together": "Iblis declared his intention to mislead all of humanity without exception. His goal is comprehensive corruption—he wants every human being to end up in Hell with him. He works tirelessly across all generations, all cultures, and all circumstances to achieve this. This is a sworn enemy who never sleeps, never gives up, and knows human weaknesses intimately."
  },
  40: {
    "except Your chosen servants among them.\"": "Even in his arrogant declaration, Iblis acknowledged a crucial exception—he admitted he would have no power over Allah's sincere, chosen servants (mukhlaseen). These are the believers who have purified their faith, making their worship exclusively for Allah. They have fortified themselves with true faith, constant remembrance of Allah, and sincere devotion. Satan knows his whispers will not penetrate hearts that are filled with Allah's light. This admission from Satan himself should give every believer hope—if you sincerely turn to Allah and purify your intentions, Satan cannot overpower you. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught us that Satan flees when he hears the call to prayer and that sincere believers are protected by their faith."
  },
  41: {
    "Allah said, \"This is the Way, binding on Me": "Allah declared a binding principle—a straight path that represents His justice and promise. Some scholars understand this to mean that the straight path leads to Allah and is under His protection. Others understand it as Allah affirming that this arrangement—the test of humanity with Satan as the tempter and sincere faith as the protection—is a matter decided by Him. Either way, this verse establishes that Allah has set clear rules for this cosmic test, and He Himself guarantees to uphold them."
  },
  42: {
    "you will certainly have no authority over My servants": "Allah confirmed what Satan himself admitted—he will have no power, dominance, or authority over Allah's true servants. The word 'sultan' means authority or compelling power. Satan cannot force anyone to sin. He can only whisper, suggest, tempt, and beautify falsehood. The choice always remains with the human being. This is tremendously empowering—you are never helpless against Satan. With Allah's help, you can always resist.",
    "except the deviant who follow you": "The only ones who fall under Satan's influence are those who willingly choose to follow him—the 'ghawoon' (the deviant, the astray). These are people who, despite having access to guidance, choose to listen to Satan's whispers and follow their base desires. They are not forced; they volunteer for their own destruction. This exception places full responsibility on those who go astray—they cannot blame Satan on the Day of Judgment because the choice was always theirs."
  },
  43: {
    "and surely Hell is their destined place, all together": "Allah declared the final destination of Satan and all who follow him—Jahannam (Hell). The word 'maw'id' means a promised appointment or destined meeting place. This is not a possibility but a certainty. Everyone who chooses to follow Satan's path—whether jinn or human—will gather in Hell together. The companionship they kept in sin will continue in punishment. Just as they united in disobedience in this world, they will be united in torment in the next. This should make every person carefully consider who they choose as companions and whose voice they listen to."
  },
  44: {
    "It has seven gates": "Hell is described as having seven gates or levels. This indicates different degrees of punishment corresponding to different levels of sin and disbelief. Just as Paradise has multiple levels of reward, Hell has multiple levels of punishment. The most severe level is at the bottom, reserved for the worst offenders like the hypocrites.",
    "to each a group of them is designated": "Allah has already decreed which gate each group of sinners will enter. The punishment is precisely matched to the crime—this is divine justice in action. Each person will receive exactly what they deserve, no more and no less. The distribution is predetermined based on Allah's complete knowledge of each person's deeds, intentions, and circumstances. This detailed organization shows that the Day of Judgment will be conducted with perfect order and justice, not chaos."
  },
  45: {
    "Indeed, the righteous will be amid Gardens": "After describing the fate of the disbelievers, Allah presents the contrasting destiny of the muttaqeen—those who had taqwa (God-consciousness, piety, mindfulness of Allah). They will dwell in gardens (jannaat)—the plural indicates multiple, vast, beautiful gardens beyond human imagination. These are places of eternal beauty, comfort, and pleasure, prepared by Allah for those who believed and did righteous deeds.",
    "and springs": "Alongside the gardens are flowing springs ('uyoon) of water, wine, honey, and other pure drinks. Unlike earthly gardens that can dry up, these springs are eternal and abundant. Water symbolizes life, purity, and refreshment—the people of Paradise will never experience thirst or deprivation. Every comfort they desired but could not have in this world, or sacrificed for Allah's sake, will be available to them in abundance."
  },
  46: {
    "˹It will be said to them,˺ \"Enter in peace": "The people of Paradise will be welcomed with words of peace (salaam). This is not just a greeting but a state of being—they enter into perfect peace. No more anxiety, no more conflict, no more pain. All the struggles of worldly life are behind them. The angels will greet them at every gate with salaam, and Allah Himself will grant them His peace.",
    "and security.\"": "Along with peace comes complete security (amineen). In this world, even the wealthy and powerful live in fear—fear of loss, fear of enemies, fear of death. In Paradise, there is absolute security from every kind of harm or threat. No one will ever take away what they have. They are safe from punishment, from expulsion, from death, from any form of suffering. This eternal security is one of the greatest gifts of Paradise."
  },
  47: {
    "We will remove whatever bitterness they had in their hearts": "Allah will purify the hearts of the people of Paradise from any grudges, jealousy, resentment, or ill feelings (ghill) they may have harbored in this world. Even believers sometimes have conflicts with each other in this life—old wounds, misunderstandings, or grievances. Allah will cleanse all of this away before they enter Paradise. This purification ensures that Paradise is truly a place of pure joy, with no lingering negativity from worldly life.",
    "In a friendly manner, they will be on thrones, facing one another": "The people of Paradise will sit on elevated, dignified thrones (surur), facing each other in friendship and love. They will enjoy each other's company without any barriers or discomfort. The positioning 'facing one another' indicates intimate, joyful gatherings—friends and loved ones spending eternity together in happiness. The social aspect of Paradise is emphasized here; it is not just individual pleasure but shared joy with beloved companions. Those who were separated in this world by death or distance will be reunited forever."
  },
  48: {
    "No fatigue will touch them there": "In this world, even pleasurable activities eventually lead to tiredness. We grow exhausted from work, from travel, even from entertainment. In Paradise, there is no fatigue (nasab) whatsoever. The people of Paradise can enjoy all pleasures indefinitely without ever feeling tired, bored, or overwhelmed. Their bodies and souls will be renewed in perfection, never subject to weakness or decline.",
    "nor will they ever be asked to leave": "Perhaps the greatest comfort of Paradise is its permanence. Unlike worldly pleasures that come to an end, Paradise is eternal. No one will ever be expelled or asked to leave. There is no checkout time, no expiration date, no fear of losing what you have. This permanence addresses a deep human anxiety—the fear that good things don't last. In Paradise, they last forever. This is the ultimate security and the ultimate reward for those who believed and remained patient in this temporary world."
  },
  49: {
    "Inform My servants ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah commands the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to convey this message to humanity. The fact that Allah calls them 'My servants' ('ibadi) shows His care and ownership—we belong to Him, and He is addressing us with guidance for our own benefit.",
    "that I am truly the All-Forgiving": "Al-Ghafoor—The One who forgives sins abundantly, no matter how many or how great. Allah's forgiveness is vast enough to cover any sin if the person sincerely repents. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Allah is more pleased with the repentance of His servant than one of you who finds his lost camel in the desert.' No sin is too large for Allah's forgiveness if approached with genuine repentance.",
    "Most Merciful": "Ar-Raheem—The One who shows mercy to those who turn to Him. His mercy is especially bestowed upon the believers in this life and the next. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Allah has divided mercy into one hundred parts. He kept ninety-nine parts with Him and sent down one part to earth. From that one part comes all the compassion creatures show to one another.' This gives hope to every sinner—no matter how far you have strayed, Allah's mercy awaits your return."
  },
  50: {
    "and that My torment is indeed the most painful": "Immediately after emphasizing His mercy, Allah balances the message by reminding us of His punishment. His torment ('adhab) is described as 'aleem—intensely painful, excruciating. This balance is crucial for a healthy faith. Hope without fear leads to complacency and sin. Fear without hope leads to despair. A believer must hold both in balance—hopeful in Allah's mercy while mindful of His punishment. The early Muslims understood this well. When asked about how to approach Allah, scholars would say: 'Fly to Allah with both wings—the wing of hope and the wing of fear.' This verse encapsulates that balance perfectly. Allah is calling us to repentance through both encouragement and warning, inviting us to His mercy while cautioning us against taking it for granted."
  },
  51: {
    "And inform them ˹O Prophet˺ about Abraham's guests": "Allah commands Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to relate this important story to his people. The story of Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham, peace be upon him) and his angelic guests contains profound lessons about faith, mercy, and divine justice. Ibrahim is one of the greatest prophets, the father of many prophets, and the patriarch revered by Muslims, Christians, and Jews alike. The 'guests' mentioned here were actually angels in human form, sent by Allah with a dual mission—to give good news to Ibrahim and to execute punishment upon the wicked people of Lot."
  },
  52: {
    "who entered upon him and greeted ˹him with˺, \"Peace!\"": "The angels came to Ibrahim's home and greeted him with 'Salaam' (peace)—the greeting of Islam and the greeting of Paradise. Ibrahim was known for his exceptional hospitality; he would often wait by the road to invite travelers to his home. When these strangers arrived, he welcomed them as any honored guest.",
    "He ˹later˺ said, \"Surely we are afraid of you.\"": "Ibrahim's fear arose after he served them food and they did not eat. In Arab culture, a guest who refuses to eat is viewed with suspicion—eating together creates a bond of trust and safety. When the angels did not touch the food, Ibrahim sensed something unusual and became apprehensive. This detail shows Ibrahim's human side—even prophets experience normal human emotions like fear. His suspicion was also a sign of his wisdom and perceptiveness."
  },
  53: {
    "They reassured ˹him˺, \"Do not be afraid!": "The angels immediately calmed Ibrahim's fears, revealing that they meant him no harm. They understood why he was concerned and addressed it directly. This shows the gentle and considerate nature of these noble messengers.",
    "Surely we give you good news of a knowledgeable son.\"": "The angels delivered tremendous news—Ibrahim and his wife Sarah would be blessed with a son who would be characterized by great knowledge ('aleem). This son would be Prophet Ishaq (Isaac, peace be upon him), who would carry on the prophetic lineage. The description 'knowledgeable' indicated this child would be special—not just any son, but a prophet and a source of guidance. This news came after Ibrahim and Sarah had spent their entire lives without children together, making it an extraordinary blessing."
  },
  54: {
    "He wondered, \"Do you give me good news despite my old age?": "Ibrahim expressed natural human amazement. He was approximately 100 years old at this time, and his wife Sarah was around 90—both well beyond the natural age of having children. His question was not one of doubt in Allah's power, but of astonishment at this unexpected blessing. Sometimes Allah's gifts come when we least expect them and when they seem most impossible by worldly standards.",
    "What unlikely news!\"": "Ibrahim marveled at the extraordinary nature of this promise. He was not denying the possibility—he knew Allah could do anything—but expressing wonder at being chosen for such a miracle at such an advanced age. This reaction is human and relatable; when we receive unexpectedly good news, we sometimes need a moment to process it."
  },
  55: {
    "They responded, \"We give you good news in all truth": "The angels confirmed that their news was absolutely true and certain. It was not a possibility or a hope—it was a divine decree that would definitely come to pass. When Allah promises something, it is as good as done. The angels wanted Ibrahim to understand that this was not mere speculation but a guaranteed reality from Allah.",
    "so do not be one of those who despair.\"": "The angels gently advised Ibrahim not to fall into despair (qunoot). Despair of Allah's mercy is a serious spiritual ailment that believers must avoid. No matter how impossible something seems by human standards, nothing is impossible for Allah. The angels' advice applies to all believers—never lose hope in Allah's ability to change your circumstances, answer your prayers, or grant you what seems beyond reach."
  },
  56: {
    "He exclaimed, \"Who would despair of the mercy of their Lord except the misguided?\"": "Ibrahim's response revealed the depth of his faith. He clarified that he was not despairing at all—he was simply amazed. He then made a profound statement: only those who are astray (dalleen) would despair of Allah's mercy. This teaches us that despair is actually a sign of misguidance, not piety. A true believer always maintains hope in Allah, no matter how dire the circumstances. Ibrahim's faith was unshakeable—he knew that Allah's mercy encompasses everything and that nothing is beyond His power. This statement has become a foundational principle in Islamic spirituality: never despair of Allah's mercy, for doing so is itself a form of disbelief in His infinite power and compassion."
  },
  57: {
    "He ˹then˺ added, \"What is your mission, O messenger-angels?\"": "After receiving the good news about his son, Ibrahim sensed there was more to this visit. Angels do not typically appear in human form just to deliver happy news—their visible appearance usually indicates something significant. Ibrahim, with his prophetic insight, directly asked about their true purpose. He addressed them as 'mursaloon' (messengers), acknowledging that they were sent by Allah on an important mission."
  },
  58: {
    "They replied, \"We have actually been sent to a wicked people.\"": "The angels revealed their primary mission—they were sent to destroy a criminal nation. The word 'mujrimeen' (criminals, wicked people) refers to the people of Lot, who had become infamous for their unprecedented sins, particularly homosexual practices and highway robbery. These people had rejected Prophet Lot's warnings repeatedly and had reached a point of no return in their transgression. Allah's patience had limits, and the time for their punishment had arrived."
  },
  59: {
    "As for the family of Lot, we will certainly deliver them all": "The angels assured Ibrahim that not all would perish—the family of Prophet Lot (peace be upon him) would be saved. Allah's punishment is precise and just; it does not destroy the innocent along with the guilty. Lot and his believing family members would be extracted from the city before the punishment descended. This demonstrates Allah's mercy even in the midst of His wrath—He protects those who believe and obey."
  },
  60: {
    "except his wife. We have determined that she will be one of the doomed.\"": "There was one exception to the family's salvation—Lot's own wife. Despite being married to a prophet and living in a household of faith, she secretly sympathized with the disbelieving townspeople. She would inform them of Lot's guests and undermine his mission. Her physical proximity to a prophet could not save her because her heart was with the disbelievers. This teaches a crucial lesson: faith is individual, and family ties or proximity to righteous people cannot substitute for personal belief. Each person is responsible for their own choices. The Quran mentions her alongside the wife of Noah as examples of women who were doomed despite their connection to prophets (Quran 66:10)."
  },
  61: {
    "So when the messengers came to the family of Lot": "After leaving Ibrahim, the angels traveled to the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah where Prophet Lot resided. They appeared as handsome young men, which would soon create a dangerous situation given the nature of the townspeople. Allah sent them in this form as a final test for the wicked people—their response would seal their fate."
  },
  62: {
    "he said, \"You are surely an unfamiliar people!\"": "When Lot saw these strangers, he was filled with concern. He did not recognize them as locals, and he knew exactly what the men of his town did to attractive strangers. The word 'munkaroon' suggests people who are unknown and whose presence causes concern. Lot's worry was not for himself but for these guests and for the shame that might befall him if his people acted upon their evil desires. He was caught in an impossible situation—hospitality demanded he welcome them, but he knew the danger they faced."
  },
  63: {
    "They responded, \"We have come to you with that ˹torment˺ which they have doubted.\"": "The angels revealed their identity and purpose to Lot. They came to deliver the very punishment that the disbelievers had mocked and denied. Throughout Lot's years of preaching, the wicked people would ridicule his warnings of divine punishment, asking sarcastically when it would arrive. Now the moment had come. The word 'yamtaroon' (doubted, disputed) indicates they had argued against and denied the reality of divine punishment—soon they would experience its truth firsthand."
  },
  64: {
    "We come to you with the truth": "The angels emphasized that they brought absolute truth (al-haqq)—the reality of Allah's decree. The punishment was not a threat or a possibility anymore; it was an imminent certainty. The time for warnings had passed.",
    "and we are certainly truthful.\"": "They affirmed their complete honesty and reliability. When angels speak, they speak only truth as commanded by Allah. Lot could trust every word they said without doubt. This was also reassurance for Lot—after years of being mocked and disbelieved, here were messengers confirming that he had been right all along, and his people had been wrong."
  },
  65: {
    "So travel with your family in the dark of night": "The angels gave Lot specific instructions for escape. They were to leave during the last portion of the night, under cover of darkness, to avoid detection by the townspeople. This timing was strategic—the wicked people would be asleep or occupied, and Lot's family could slip away unnoticed.",
    "and follow ˹closely˺ behind them": "Lot was instructed to walk behind his family, ensuring no one lagged behind or got lost. As the leader, he would watch over them from the rear, making sure everyone kept moving forward toward safety. This also meant he could prevent anyone from turning back.",
    "Do not let any of you look back": "This was a crucial command—no one was to look back at the city. Looking back could indicate longing for what was left behind, attachment to the doomed place, or hesitation about leaving. It was a test of complete obedience and forward commitment. Lot's wife would later disobey this command, revealing where her heart truly lay.",
    "and go where you are commanded.\"": "They were to proceed to a specific destination designated by Allah. They should not wander or choose their own path but follow divine guidance exactly. Complete obedience in moments of crisis is essential for salvation."
  },
  66: {
    "We revealed to him this decree": "Allah communicated this decision to Lot through the angels, making the plan absolutely clear. There was no ambiguity about what was going to happen.",
    "\"Those ˹sinners˺ will be uprooted in the morning.\"": "The punishment was scheduled for the morning—specifically, at sunrise. The word 'dabir' refers to the last remnant or root of something; saying it would be 'cut off' (maqtoo') meant complete annihilation. Not a single one of those sinners would remain. By morning, the cities would be utterly destroyed, and this wicked civilization would be erased from existence. The timing was precise—Allah's decrees are always executed at exactly the appointed moment."
  },
  67: {
    "And there came the men of the city, rejoicing.": "Word spread quickly—likely through Lot's treacherous wife—that handsome young strangers were at Lot's house. The men of the city came rushing with excitement and evil anticipation. The word 'yastabshiroon' (rejoicing, receiving good news) shows their perverse excitement. What should have caused shame caused them joy. Their moral compass was completely inverted—they celebrated the opportunity to commit their disgusting acts. This public, shameless behavior demonstrated how far they had fallen; they no longer even attempted to hide their sins."
  },
  68: {
    "Lot pleaded, \"Indeed, these are my guests": "Lot appealed to the sacred institution of hospitality, which was deeply honored in ancient cultures. A host was duty-bound to protect his guests with his own life if necessary. By declaring them his guests, Lot invoked this code of honor, hoping it might restrain the mob.",
    "so do not embarrass me.\"": "Lot begged them not to bring shame upon him by violating his guests. The word 'tafdahoon' means to disgrace or humiliate. In that culture, a man who could not protect his guests suffered tremendous dishonor. Lot was appealing to whatever remained of their sense of shame and social propriety. Sadly, these people had lost all such sensibilities."
  },
  69: {
    "Fear Allah": "Lot reminded them of their Creator and Judge, the One who sees all actions and before whom they would be held accountable. This was his ultimate appeal—to whatever fear of Allah might still exist in their hearts. True taqwa (God-consciousness) would have prevented them from even considering such sins.",
    "and do not humiliate me.\"": "Lot repeated his plea for them to spare him from disgrace. He was a prophet among people who showed him no respect, constantly humiliating him and rejecting his message. The verb 'tukhzoon' (humiliate, disgrace) is even stronger than the previous 'tafdahoon.' Lot was desperate, watching his honor and his guests about to be violated by a shameless mob."
  },
  70: {
    "They responded, \"Have we not forbidden you from protecting anyone?\"": "The mob's response revealed their complete corruption. They had apparently warned Lot before to stop interfering with their crimes by offering protection to strangers. In their twisted society, they had made it a rule that Lot could not shelter anyone from their predatory behavior. They saw themselves as having authority over him, reversing the proper moral order where a prophet should guide his people. Their arrogance and shamelessness knew no bounds—they openly declared their evil and dared Lot to oppose them."
  },
  71: {
    "He said, \"O my people! Here are my daughters": "In desperation, Lot offered a lawful alternative—marriage to the women of his community. Some scholars say 'daughters' refers to his actual daughters, offered in legitimate marriage. Others say it refers to the women of the community, as a prophet is like a father to his people. Either way, Lot was trying to redirect them toward natural, lawful relationships instead of their unnatural, forbidden desires.",
    "˹so marry them˺ if you wish to do so.\"": "Lot offered them a halal (permissible) outlet if they insisted on fulfilling their desires. This shows his desperate attempt to find any solution that would prevent the greater evil. He was guiding them toward what Allah had made lawful while trying to protect his guests from what was absolutely forbidden. But these people had no interest in what was natural and permissible—they craved only what was unnatural and forbidden."
  },
  72: {
    "By your life ˹O Prophet˺": "This is an oath by Allah using the life of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), which scholars note is a unique honor—Allah swearing by the Prophet's life indicates his tremendous status. Some scholars consider this one of the greatest honors given to any prophet in the Quran.",
    "they certainly wandered blindly, intoxicated ˹by lust˺.": "Allah describes the people of Lot as being in a state of 'sakrah' (intoxication, drunkenness)—not necessarily from alcohol, but intoxicated by their own lusts and desires. They were 'ya'mahoon' (wandering blindly), stumbling in their misguidance without direction or sense. When a person becomes enslaved to their desires, they lose the ability to think clearly or see the truth. Their desires had completely overtaken their reason, and they could not perceive the destruction that was moments away."
  },
  73: {
    "So the ˹mighty˺ blast overtook them at sunrise.": "Exactly as decreed, the punishment came at sunrise (mushriqeen—when the sun rose). The 'sayhah' was a tremendous blast—a catastrophic sound that destroyed everything. Some scholars describe it as an earthquake accompanied by a deafening sound. The timing was precise to the moment Allah had specified. Those who had spent the night in their evil intentions were suddenly seized by divine punishment. They had no chance to flee, no time to repent—the opportunity for that had long passed."
  },
  74: {
    "And We turned the cities ˹of Sodom and Gomorrah˺ upside down": "The destruction was complete and literal—Allah inverted the cities, turning what was on top to the bottom. This could describe a massive earthquake that flipped the terrain or the cities being lifted and thrown down. Either way, the annihilation was total. Nothing remained standing; the civilization was utterly erased.",
    "and rained upon them stones of baked clay.": "Along with the physical inversion, Allah sent a rain of 'hijaarah min sijjeel'—stones of baked clay, like hardened pottery or what some describe as burning meteors. These rained down upon the people from the sky, ensuring complete destruction. The combination of earthquake and bombardment from above left nothing and no one. The punishment matched the magnitude of their crimes—unprecedented sins met with unprecedented destruction."
  },
  75: {
    "Surely in this are signs for those who contemplate.": "Allah points out that this historical event contains clear signs (ayaat) for 'mutawassimeen'—those who reflect deeply, who can read the signs, who contemplate the lessons of history. The ruins of these cities serve as a permanent reminder of what happens when a society abandons morality completely. Those with insight can look at this story and understand: Allah is real, His warnings are true, and His punishment is certain for those who persist in grave sins while rejecting guidance."
  },
  76: {
    "Their ruins still lie along a known route.": "The remains of these destroyed cities were located along established trade routes that the Arabs of Prophet Muhammad's time would travel. When they journeyed to Syria for trade, they would pass by the area of the Dead Sea where these cities once stood. The desolate, salt-encrusted landscape served as a visual reminder of Allah's punishment. Allah mentions this so people realize that these are not mere myths but historical realities with physical evidence still visible."
  },
  77: {
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who believe.": "While the previous verse mentioned those who contemplate, this verse specifically addresses believers (mu'mineen). For those who have faith, this story is a powerful sign confirming the truth of revelation. It strengthens their conviction that Allah's promises and warnings are real. They see in this story both a warning against sin and reassurance that Allah protects the righteous (Lot and his family were saved). The believers take heed, learn the lessons, and strive to avoid the path that leads to such destruction."
  },
  78: {
    "And the residents of the Forest were truly wrongdoers": "The 'Ashaab al-Aykah' (Companions of the Thicket or Forest) were the people of Prophet Shu'ayb (peace be upon him), also known as the people of Madyan. They lived in a lush, forested area and were known for their corrupt business practices—cheating in weights and measures, highway robbery, and rejecting the message of their prophet. The word 'Aykah' refers to dense, intertwined trees, indicating they lived in a fertile, prosperous land. Despite their blessings, they were 'dhalimeen' (wrongdoers, oppressors)—they wronged themselves through disbelief and wronged others through their dishonest dealings. Their prosperity did not lead them to gratitude but to arrogance and transgression."
  },
  79: {
    "so We inflicted punishment upon them": "Allah executed His vengeance (intiqam) upon them for their persistent wrongdoing and rejection of Prophet Shu'ayb. Their punishment came in the form of scorching heat followed by a devastating blast. After days of unbearable heat, they sought shade under a cloud, which then unleashed upon them fire and destruction. This was divine justice for a people who refused to repent.",
    "The ruins of both nations still lie on a well-known road.": "The pronoun 'both' (inhuma) refers to the people of Lot and the people of the Forest—both of their destroyed settlements were located along trade routes familiar to the Arabs. The word 'imam' here means a clear road or path. Travelers passing through these areas could see the remnants of these destroyed civilizations, serving as visible warnings and lessons. Allah placed these ruins strategically so that people would be reminded of the fate of those who rejected divine guidance."
  },
  80: {
    "Indeed, the residents of the Stone Valley also denied the messengers": "The 'Ashaab al-Hijr' were the people of Thamud, who lived in the rocky valley of Al-Hijr (modern-day Mada'in Saleh in Saudi Arabia). They were the people of Prophet Salih (peace be upon him). Although only one messenger was sent to them, the verse uses the plural 'messengers' because rejecting one messenger is equivalent to rejecting all messengers—they all came with the same essential message of monotheism. The Thamud were powerful people who carved magnificent homes out of solid rock, demonstrating advanced architectural skills and seeming permanence."
  },
  81: {
    "We gave them Our signs": "Allah blessed the Thamud with clear signs, the most notable being the miraculous she-camel that emerged from a rock at Prophet Salih's prayer. This camel was a living miracle—it would drink from the well on one day while the entire tribe drank on alternate days, and it provided abundant milk for all. This sign should have been undeniable proof of Salih's prophethood.",
    "but they turned away from them": "Despite witnessing this clear miracle, they turned away in arrogance. The word 'mu'rideen' indicates deliberate, willful turning away—not ignorance or confusion, but conscious rejection. They not only ignored the signs but eventually killed the miraculous she-camel in defiance of Prophet Salih's warnings. Their rejection was active rebellion, not passive disbelief."
  },
  82: {
    "They carved their homes in the mountains, feeling secure": "The Thamud possessed remarkable engineering capabilities—they carved elaborate dwellings directly into mountain rock. These homes were cool in summer, warm in winter, and seemingly impervious to any attack or natural disaster. The word 'amineen' (feeling secure) reveals their psychological state: they believed their rock fortresses made them invincible. They felt safe from any threat, including divine punishment. This false sense of security made them even more arrogant. Their impressive constructions, however, could not protect them from Allah's decree. No fortress, no matter how strong, can shield someone from their Lord."
  },
  83: {
    "But the ˹mighty˺ blast overtook them in the morning": "Just like the people of Lot, the Thamud were destroyed by a 'sayhah'—a catastrophic blast. This overwhelming sound came at morning (musbiheeen), the time when they would normally rise to begin their day in their 'secure' mountain homes. The same morning sun that they expected to see rose upon their utter destruction. Prophet Salih had warned them they had three days to repent after killing the she-camel; they did not, and the punishment came exactly as promised."
  },
  84: {
    "and all they achieved was of no help to them": "Their wealth, their power, their sophisticated rock-carved homes, their engineering prowess—none of it benefited them when Allah's punishment arrived. The word 'yaksibuoon' (what they earned/achieved) encompasses all their worldly accomplishments. Everything they had worked for, everything they took pride in, became worthless in an instant. This is a profound lesson about the futility of worldly achievements when disconnected from faith and obedience to Allah. The ruins of their magnificent dwellings still stand today at Mada'in Saleh, a haunting reminder of a civilization that thought it was invincible."
  },
  85: {
    "We have not created the heavens and the earth and everything in between except for a purpose": "Allah reminds the Prophet (peace be upon him) and all of humanity that creation is not random or meaningless. The universe, with all its complexity and beauty, was created 'bil-haqq' (with truth, purpose, and wisdom). There is meaning behind existence, and there is accountability coming. Understanding this gives perspective during difficulties—nothing is pointless, and justice will ultimately prevail.",
    "And the Hour is certain to come": "The Day of Judgment is an absolute certainty (la-aatiyah—definitely coming). All wrongs will be addressed, all oppressors will face justice, and all the patient believers will be rewarded. This reminder helps the Prophet endure the mockery and rejection he faces—these disbelievers will not escape accountability.",
    "so forgive graciously": "Given this reality, Allah advises the Prophet to practice 'safh jameel' (beautiful, gracious forgiveness). Rather than seeking revenge or becoming bitter, the Prophet should overlook the offenses of his enemies with dignity and grace. This does not mean accepting falsehood, but rather not letting their hostility disturb his inner peace or distract him from his mission. The Prophet embodied this quality throughout his life, famously forgiving even his worst enemies when he conquered Makkah."
  },
  86: {
    "Surely your Lord is the Master Creator": "Allah is 'Al-Khallaq'—the One who creates continuously, abundantly, and perfectly. This intensive form indicates that Allah's creative power is unlimited and ongoing. Everything that exists comes from Him, and He continues creating at every moment. This reminds the Prophet that the same Lord who created entire universes is fully capable of handling the enemies of Islam.",
    "All-Knowing": "Allah is 'Al-'Aleem'—completely aware of everything, including the plots of the disbelievers, the suffering of the Prophet, and the best resolution for all situations. Nothing is hidden from Him. This combination of infinite creative power and complete knowledge means that Allah's plan is perfect, and the Prophet can trust fully in His Lord's wisdom and timing."
  },
  87: {
    "We have certainly granted you the seven often-repeated verses": "Allah reminds the Prophet of the immense gift he has received. The 'seven often-repeated' (sab'an min al-mathani) refers to Surah Al-Fatihah, which consists of seven verses and is repeated in every unit of prayer. Some scholars also include other interpretations, but the majority view is that this refers to Al-Fatihah—the greatest chapter of the Quran. It is called 'mathani' because it is repeated frequently and because its meanings are paired (praise and supplication, guidance and warning).",
    "and the great Quran": "Beyond Al-Fatihah, the Prophet received the entire Quran—described as 'adheem' (great, magnificent). The Quran is the greatest of all scriptures, the final and complete revelation, a miracle that will remain until the Day of Judgment. Having this gift far outweighs any worldly possessions the disbelievers might enjoy. This verse redirects the Prophet's focus from what others have to what he has been given—the greatest gift imaginable."
  },
  88: {
    "Do not let your eyes crave the ˹fleeting˺ pleasures We have provided for some of the disbelievers": "Allah instructs the Prophet (and through him, all believers) not to look longingly at the worldly enjoyments of the disbelievers. The phrase 'la tamuddanna' (do not extend your gaze) warns against desiring what others have. Some disbelievers were wealthy, powerful, and seemed to be enjoying life without any concern for faith. But these are temporary provisions (mata'na)—fleeting pleasures that will end. What the Prophet has (the Quran, prophethood, connection to Allah) is eternal and infinitely more valuable.",
    "nor grieve for them": "The Prophet should not exhaust himself with sorrow over those who refuse to believe. He delivered the message faithfully; their rejection is their loss, not his failure. Excessive grief over others' disbelief can drain a person's energy and distract from productive work. The Prophet cared deeply about all people, but Allah is teaching him to maintain emotional balance.",
    "And be gracious to the believers": "The beautiful phrase 'ikhfid janahaka' literally means 'lower your wing'—an image of a bird lowering its wing to shelter and protect its young. The Prophet should extend gentleness, compassion, and humility to the believers. Rather than focusing on the stubborn disbelievers, he should nurture and care for those who have accepted faith. This prioritization is important: invest your energy in those who are receptive, while not being harsh to anyone."
  },
  89: {
    "And say, \"I am truly sent with a clear warning\"": "Allah instructs the Prophet to declare his role clearly and unambiguously. He is 'nadheer mubeen'—a warner whose message is plain and evident. His job is to warn people of the consequences of disbelief and disobedience. The warning is clear, not obscure or complicated. Anyone who hears it and understands it has no excuse for ignoring it. This clarity removes any argument the disbelievers might make on the Day of Judgment that they did not understand or were not warned properly."
  },
  90: {
    "˹a warning˺ similar to what We sent to those who divided ˹the Scriptures˺": "The warning the Prophet brings is similar to warnings sent to previous nations. The 'muqtasimeen' (those who divided) refers to people—either from among the Jews, Christians, or the Quraysh themselves—who divided scriptures and guidance according to their whims. They accepted parts that suited them and rejected parts that challenged them. This selective approach to divine guidance is a serious sin that merits severe warning."
  },
  91: {
    "who ˹now˺ accept parts of the Quran, rejecting others": "These people treated the Quran (or previous scriptures) as 'ideen'—broken into pieces. They would accept verses that aligned with their desires or pre-existing beliefs while rejecting or ignoring verses that challenged them. Some would call parts of the Quran poetry, other parts magic, and other parts outdated stories—anything to avoid accepting it as a unified divine revelation. This picking and choosing from Allah's guidance is unacceptable; true faith means accepting guidance completely, even when it challenges us."
  },
  92: {
    "So by your Lord! We will certainly question them all": "Allah swears by Himself—the most emphatic oath possible—that every single one of these people will be questioned. The word 'ajma'een' (all of them) emphasizes that no one will escape this questioning. Every individual, regardless of status, wealth, or power, will stand before Allah and be asked about their response to guidance. This is a solemn promise that accountability is certain."
  },
  93: {
    "about what they used to do": "The questioning will cover all their actions (ya'maloon)—their rejection of truth, their mockery of prophets, their division of scriptures, their sins, and their refusal to repent. Every deed, word, and even intention will be examined. This should motivate every person to evaluate their actions now, before that Day when excuses will not help. The good news is that those who believed and did righteous deeds will also be questioned—and their answers will lead to eternal reward."
  },
  94: {
    "So proclaim what you have been commanded": "The word 'isda' (proclaim) comes from a root meaning to split or break through. The Prophet is told to break through the barriers of opposition and openly proclaim the message without fear or hesitation. Until this point, some preaching had been done quietly; now Allah commands open, bold declaration of the truth. This verse marked a turning point in the prophetic mission—from private invitation to public proclamation.",
    "and turn away from the polytheists": "The Prophet should not waste energy arguing endlessly with those committed to polytheism. 'Turn away' (a'rid) means to not be affected by their mockery or deterred by their opposition. It does not mean to stop preaching to them, but to not let their negative response shake his resolve. Focus on delivering the message; their acceptance or rejection is not his responsibility."
  },
  95: {
    "Surely We will be sufficient for you against the mockers": "This is a powerful divine promise of protection. Allah Himself will handle those who mock the Prophet and the message. The 'mustahzi'een' (mockers) were a specific group of Quraysh leaders who made it their mission to ridicule the Prophet and Islam. Allah promises to deal with them—the Prophet need not worry about defending himself against their attacks. Historically, each of these mockers met an unpleasant end in various ways, fulfilling this promise. This guarantee extends beyond that specific group: Allah always protects His message and His messengers from those who seek to destroy them through ridicule."
  },
  96: {
    "who set up ˹other˺ gods with Allah": "These mockers were not just insulting the Prophet—they were committing the fundamental sin of shirk (associating partners with Allah). They worshipped idols alongside, or instead of, the One True God. This was the root of their opposition to the Prophet's message of pure monotheism. Their mockery stemmed from their desire to protect their false beliefs and the social system built around idol worship.",
    "They will soon come to know": "A warning of imminent consequences: 'sawfa ya'lamoon'—they will certainly come to know the truth. This knowledge will come either in this world through seeing Islam triumph, or at death when the veil is lifted, or certainly on the Day of Judgment when all realities become clear. Their mockery, which seems powerful now, will be shown to be utter foolishness."
  },
  97: {
    "We certainly know that your heart is truly distressed by what they say": "Allah acknowledges the emotional pain the Prophet experiences from the constant insults, mockery, and accusations of the disbelievers. The phrase 'yadeequ sadruka' (your chest becomes tight/constricted) describes the feeling of anxiety, hurt, and frustration that comes from being attacked. Allah knows this is happening—nothing is hidden from Him. This acknowledgment itself is comforting; the Prophet's Lord sees his struggle and cares about his emotional state. Every believer who faces mockery for their faith can find solace here: Allah knows what you are going through."
  },
  98: {
    "So glorify the praises of your Lord": "The remedy for distress is given: engage in 'tasbeeh' (glorifying Allah) combined with 'hamd' (praising Him). When overwhelmed by the attacks of others, turn to Allah with worship. Say 'SubhanAllah' (Glory be to Allah) and 'Alhamdulillah' (All praise is due to Allah). This redirects focus from the painful situation to the greatness of Allah, putting problems in perspective. Remembrance of Allah brings peace to the heart, as stated elsewhere in the Quran: 'Verily, in the remembrance of Allah do hearts find rest' (13:28).",
    "and be one of those who ˹always˺ pray": "Along with verbal glorification, the Prophet is instructed to engage in prayer (sujood represents prayer, as prostration is its most honored position). Regular prayer provides a structured time to connect with Allah, unburden the heart, and receive spiritual strength. Prayer is not just a ritual but a therapeutic connection with the Creator. The Prophet (peace be upon him) would say: 'O Bilal, give us comfort through prayer (aqim as-salah).' Prayer was his source of relief in times of difficulty."
  },
  99: {
    "and worship your Lord until the inevitable comes your way": "Allah commands continuous worship—not just in times of difficulty, but always, until 'al-yaqeen' (the certainty) arrives. 'Al-yaqeen' here refers to death, which is called 'certainty' because it is the one thing every person is absolutely certain to experience. This verse establishes that worship is a lifelong obligation. There is no retirement from serving Allah, no age at which one has 'done enough.' The Prophet, and every believer after him, is to remain devoted to Allah until their last breath. This final verse of the surah provides a comprehensive life program: worship Allah consistently, through good times and bad, until you meet Him. This is the path to peace in this life and eternal success in the next."
  }
};